<subSubSection id="C3776556EEC33BA7FF78FDEDFD1BFD62" pageId="402" pageNumber="403" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEEC33BA7FF78FDEDFD1BFD62" blockId="402.[136,778,173,1832]" pageId="402" pageNumber="403">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEC33BA7FF78FDEDFEFBFDFC" bold="true" box="[189,318,547,573]" pageId="402" pageNumber="403">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name of the new genus is from the Greek 
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEC33BA7FF13FD8BFEC0FD9E" box="[214,261,581,607]" italics="true" pageId="402" pageNumber="403">chel</emphasis>
(=claw) and 
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEC33BA7FE65FD88FE24FD9E" box="[416,481,582,607]" italics="true" pageId="402" pageNumber="403">pygus</emphasis>
, the ending of many taxa within the family 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEEC33BA7FE8EFDA9FDC7FD40" authorityName="Dana" authorityYear="1853" box="[331,514,615,641]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="402" pageNumber="403" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Notodelphyidae</taxonomicName>
. It refers to the presence of the spines on the caudal ramus. Gender masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
